[Assistant] The answer is yes — and it's obvious once you see it. The right data is already in scope at write time.

**The problem:** `topic_signal` is currently set only from `extract_topic_signal(input)` — a text pattern extractor looking for file paths and feature ID strings in query content. Most observations (60-70%) don't have those patterns, so they get `NULL`.

**What's already available:** At the exact point every observation is written, `session_registry` is in scope. `session_registry.get_state(session_id)` returns `SessionState`, which has a `feature: Option<String>` field — the in-memory attribution set **synchronously** by `set_feature_force` when `context_cycle(start)` is called. This is the most reliable signal in the system — not an async DB write, not text extraction, just a synchronous mutex update.

**The fix:** two lines, two places in `listener.rs`:

```rust
// context_search path (line 824) — today:
let topic_signal = unimatrix_observe::extract_topic_signal(&query);

// after fix:
let topic_signal = unimatrix_observe::extract_topic_signal(&query)
    .or_else(|| session_registry.get_state(sid).and_then(|s| s.feature));
```

```rust
// RecordEvent path (line 684) — today:
let obs = extract_observation_fields(&event);

// after fix:
let mut obs = extract_observation_fields(&event);
if obs.topic_signal.is_none() {
    obs.topic_signal = session_registry.get_state(&event.session_id)
        .and_then(|s| s.feature);
}
```

Text-extracted signal wins when present (higher precision — it can detect mid-session feature switches). Session registry feature is the fallback.

**What this means for coverage:** every observation written after `context_cycle(start)` gets `topic_signal` set. The 1-11% becomes ~100% for any post-cycle session. This makes the col-024 redesign much more reliable — instead of identifying sessions from a handful of signal hits, you'd have dense, consistent attribution throughout.

**One nuance:** this only improves future observations. Existing mis-attributed sessions in prod still need the cycle-window approach. Both changes are complementary — col-024 fixes the lookup for existing data, this improvement makes future data self-attributing.

Worth scoping this as part of col-024 since it directly strengthens the new primary path. Ready to save this design and open the issue?
